04352nam a22005775i 9780226367101DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263671017 a10.7208/97802263671012doi  a(DE-B1597)524141  a(OCoLC)946887835  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHJ6622b.R36 2017 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a382.70973090332231 aRao, Gautham, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNational Duties :bCustom Houses and the Making of the American State /cGautham Rao. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b10 halftones, 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Beginnings, 1500-190000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Archival Sources -- tIntroduction -- t1. Custom Houses, Negotiated Authority, and the Bonds of Empire, 1714- 1776 -- t2. Political Economy and the Making of the Customs System -- t3. Negotiating Authority in Federalist America, 1789- 1800 -- t4. Commerce or War? -- t5. Jefferson's Embargo and the Era of Commercial Restrictions, 1807- 1815 -- t6. Dismantling Discretion, 1816- 1828 -- tEpilogue: Charleston, 1832 -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the wake of the American Revolution, if you had asked a citizen whether his fledgling state would survive more than two centuries, the answer would have been far from confident. The problem, as is so often the case, was money. Left millions of dollars of debt by the war, the nascent federal government created a system of taxes on imported goods and installed custom houses at the nation's ports, which were charged with collecting these fees. Gradually, the houses amassed enough revenue from import merchants to stabilize the new government. But, as the fragile United States was dependent on this same revenue, the merchants at the same time gained outsized influence over the daily affairs of the custom houses. As the United States tried to police this commerce in the early nineteenth century, the merchants' stranglehold on custom house governance proved to be formidable. In National Duties, Gautham Rao makes the case that the origins of the federal government and the modern American state lie in these conflicts at government custom houses between the American Revolution and the presidency of Andrew Jackson. He argues that the contours of the government emerged from the push-and-pull between these groups, with commercial interests gradually losing power to the administrative state, which only continued to grow and lives on today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCustoms administration - England - Colonies - America. 0aCustoms administrationxColonieszEnglandzAmerica. 0aCustoms administrationzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226367101423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226367101.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3  UChP eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles